            {'question': 'A farmer notices yellowing leaves on their wheat crop. How would you diagnose and treat this?', 'answer': 'Diagnostic process: 1) Pattern Analysis: Uniform yellowing = nutrient deficiency or waterlogging. Patchy yellowing = disease or pest damage. 2) Leaf Position: Lower/older leaves yellow first = nitrogen deficiency (most common). Upper/new leaves = iron or sulfur deficiency. Interveinal yellowing = magnesium or manganese deficiency. 3) Soil Test: Check pH (wheat prefers 6.0-7.0), nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium levels. 4) Check Roots: Waterlogged roots turn brown—improve drainage. 5) Treatment: Nitrogen deficiency—apply urea (46% N) at 50-60 kg/hectare. Iron deficiency—foliar spray of ferrous sulfate. 6) Prevention: Balanced fertilization based on soil testing, proper irrigation scheduling.', 'type': 'scenario'},
