            {'question': 'A customer complains their car pulls to the left while braking. What could be the cause?', 'answer': 'Possible causes: 1) Uneven Brake Pad Wear: Left side pads worn more than right—replace both sides. 2) Stuck Caliper: Right caliper not engaging fully—clean, lubricate, or replace caliper slides. 3) Brake Fluid Leak: Reduced pressure on one side—inspect brake lines, hoses, and cylinders for leaks. 4) Contaminated Brake Pad: Oil or grease on one side\'s pads—replace pads, fix the contamination source. 5) Warped Rotor: Uneven rotor surface causes inconsistent braking—measure rotor thickness variation, resurface or replace if beyond tolerance (typically >0.025mm variation). 6) Tire Issues: Unequal tire pressure or worn tires can also cause pulling—check and equalize pressures first (easiest fix).', 'type': 'scenario'},
